<doc id="632685" wikidata="Q9388290" url="?curid=632685" title="Coimage">
<text>In algebra, the coimage of a homomorphism

:formula_1

is the quotient

:formula_2

of the domain by the kernel. 
The coimage is canonically isomorphic to the image by the first isomorphism theorem, when that theorem applies.

More generally, in category theory, the coimage of a morphism is the dual notion of the image of a morphism. If formula_3, then a coimage of formula_4 (if it exists) is an epimorphism formula_5 such that
#there is a map formula_6 with formula_7,
#for any epimorphism formula_8 for which there is a map formula_9 with formula_10, there is a unique map formula_11 such that both formula_12 and formula_13

